WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.744
Last time, we were talking
about the energies of the

00:00:14.744 --> 00:00:18.558
various states in the
multi-electron atom.

00:00:18.558 --> 00:00:21.906
Now, the question is,
experimentally,

00:00:21.906 --> 00:00:25.441
how do we know what these
energies are?

00:00:25.441 --> 00:00:30.000
How do we know these energy
levels exist?

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.580
And the primary technique that
we have to know that is

00:00:34.580 --> 00:00:38.814
something called X-ray
photoelectron spectroscopy.

00:00:38.814 --> 00:00:43.049
And X-ray photoelectron
spectroscopy uses the same

00:00:43.049 --> 00:00:47.888
principle that we talked about
when we talked about photo

00:00:47.888 --> 00:00:52.641
emission or the photoelectric
effect really explained by

00:00:52.641 --> 00:00:54.802
Einstein.
And, by the way,

00:00:54.802 --> 00:00:59.296
I put on the website a very
comprehensible article on

00:00:59.296 --> 00:01:05.000
Einstein's contribution to the
photoelectric effect.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.606
This is something that just
came out in a journal just very

00:01:10.606 --> 00:01:15.343
recently and I saw it.
And so I urge you to take a

00:01:15.343 --> 00:01:21.336
look at it because it really is
very understandable and kind of

00:01:21.336 --> 00:01:27.523
fills in some of the gaps that I
left in talking about the actual

00:01:27.523 --> 00:01:34.000
problems, some of the kind of
sociological effects or gaps.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.141
All right.
So same idea,

00:01:36.141 --> 00:01:41.633
photoelectron spectroscopy and
that we come in with a photon

00:01:41.633 --> 00:01:45.543
and that induced an electron to
be emitted.

00:01:45.543 --> 00:01:50.384
But unlike the photoelectron
spectroscopy on a solid,

00:01:50.384 --> 00:01:54.666
where we essentially had just
one energy level,

00:01:54.666 --> 00:01:59.972
in photoelectron spectroscopy
on atoms we're going to have

00:01:59.972 --> 00:02:05.000
many energy levels,
as we've already seen.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.967
And the photon that we're going
to use, that photon is going to

00:02:09.967 --> 00:02:14.535
have an energy so that in
principle it can pull out of the

00:02:14.535 --> 00:02:17.500
atom the most strongly-bound
electron.

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:21.185
And if we want that,
well, then that means that

00:02:21.185 --> 00:02:25.673
we're going to have to use a
pretty energetic photon and,

00:02:25.673 --> 00:02:30.000
that is, we're going to use an
X-ray photon.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.782
So it works in the following
way.

00:02:32.782 --> 00:02:36.086
Let's take this unsuspecting
neon atom.

00:02:36.086 --> 00:02:39.304
We bring in a photon,
an X-ray photon.

00:02:39.304 --> 00:02:42.869
[LAUGHTER] I'll turn it down a
little bit.

00:02:42.869 --> 00:02:45.739
Not too much.
And that, of course,

00:02:45.739 --> 00:02:48.956
one of those electrons can be
emitted.

00:02:48.956 --> 00:02:54.173
And one of the electrons that
can come off is this p electron

00:02:54.173 --> 00:02:59.391
here so that the resulting ion
configuration of the neon atom

00:02:59.391 --> 00:03:04.000
is 1s 2 2s 2 2p 5..

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.757
But also, this photon can pluck
off this s electron so that the

00:03:09.757 --> 00:03:14.957
resulting ion configuration is
1s 2 2s 1 2p 6.

00:03:14.957 --> 00:03:17.000
And, of course,

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.385
that photon can come in and
pluck off an s electron so that

00:03:22.385 --> 00:03:27.957
the resulting ion configuration
here is 1s 2 2s 2 2p 6.

00:03:27.957 --> 00:03:31.570
So that one photon,

00:03:31.570 --> 00:03:35.041
in principle,
has enough energy to pull off

00:03:35.041 --> 00:03:38.099
even the most strongly bound
electron.

00:03:38.099 --> 00:03:42.975
And then what we do in this
technique is that we measure the

00:03:42.975 --> 00:03:47.272
kinetic energies of these
electrons that are emitted,

00:03:47.272 --> 00:03:51.239
and then we plot,
simply, the number of electrons

00:03:51.239 --> 00:03:56.033
emitted at a particular energy.
We scan the kinetic energy.

00:03:56.033 --> 00:04:00.000
And a typical plot looks like
this.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.841
This is just the number of
electrons coming off with the

00:04:04.841 --> 00:04:09.242
particular kinetic energy.
And you see we see three

00:04:09.242 --> 00:04:13.995
different kinetic energies.
We see electrons coming off

00:04:13.995 --> 00:04:17.779
with 383 eVs,
electrons coming off with 1205

00:04:17.779 --> 00:04:21.036
and electrons coming off with
1232 eV.

00:04:21.036 --> 00:04:25.701
Well, of course it's going to
turn out here that those

00:04:25.701 --> 00:04:31.246
electrons that come off with the
lowest kinetic energy are those

00:04:31.246 --> 00:04:36.000
electrons that were most
strongly bound.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.725
There are those electrons that
were in that 1s state.

00:04:39.725 --> 00:04:42.161
Why?
Well, look at the energy level

00:04:42.161 --> 00:04:45.098
diagram here.
Here are those 1s electrons.

00:04:45.098 --> 00:04:49.540
Here is the incident energy of
the photon that we came in with.

00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:53.408
If these electrons are most
strongly bound then they're

00:04:53.408 --> 00:04:56.489
going to have the highest
ionization energy,

00:04:56.489 --> 00:05:00.000
the highest energy to pluck
them off.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.021
And, therefore,
in order to conserve energy,

00:05:03.021 --> 00:05:06.604
the incident energy,
the ionization energy plus that

00:05:06.604 --> 00:05:09.976
kinetic energy has to equal that
incident energy.

00:05:09.976 --> 00:05:12.716
And if this is the largest
energy, well,

00:05:12.716 --> 00:05:16.510
then those are the electrons
that are going to have the

00:05:16.510 --> 00:05:19.531
lowest kinetic energy.
So those are those 1s

00:05:19.531 --> 00:05:22.271
electrons.
That's how we identify those.

00:05:22.271 --> 00:05:26.346
And then there are electrons
coming off at 1205 where those

00:05:26.346 --> 00:05:30.000
are the electrons from the 2s
state.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.379
That's a little bit higher
energy.

00:05:32.379 --> 00:05:36.057
And so if this is the energy of
the incident photon,

00:05:36.057 --> 00:05:39.086
it's a photon coming in as the
same energy.

00:05:39.086 --> 00:05:42.187
If that's the energy of the
incident photon,

00:05:42.187 --> 00:05:46.225
this is then the ionization
energy for those electrons in

00:05:46.225 --> 00:05:49.110
that 2s state.
Well, that leftover energy

00:05:49.110 --> 00:05:53.581
then, that's the kinetic energy.
And it is a little bit greater

00:05:53.581 --> 00:05:57.764
than it was for 1s because,
again, those electrons are less

00:05:57.764 --> 00:06:02.185
strongly bound.
And then finally we have this

00:06:02.185 --> 00:06:03.768
feature here,
1232 eV.

00:06:03.768 --> 00:06:07.688
Those are the 2p electrons.
These electrons are least

00:06:07.688 --> 00:06:11.080
strongly bound.
So here is the incident energy

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:14.321
of the photon.
Here is the ionization energy

00:06:14.321 --> 00:06:16.884
of those electrons in the 2p
state.

00:06:16.884 --> 00:06:21.331
The resulting or the leftover
energy here is the energy that

00:06:21.331 --> 00:06:24.874
goes into the kinetic energy of
those electrons,

00:06:24.874 --> 00:06:30.000
and that is going to be the
largest kinetic energy --

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.286
Because those electrons are
least strongly bound.

00:06:33.286 --> 00:06:36.435
So in this neon atom,
we've got three different

00:06:36.435 --> 00:06:38.899
states with three different
energies.

00:06:38.899 --> 00:06:42.596
That is reflected in the fact
that we're going to have,

00:06:42.596 --> 00:06:46.361
in the photoelectron spectrum,
we're going to have three

00:06:46.361 --> 00:06:50.127
different kinetic energies for
the electrons coming off.

00:06:50.127 --> 00:06:53.550
So by looking at the
photoelectron spectrum you can

00:06:53.550 --> 00:06:58.000
immediately tell how many energy
levels you've got.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.819
And, of course,
as the kinetic energy goes up,

00:07:01.819 --> 00:07:05.893
well, that means that the
binding energy goes up,

00:07:05.893 --> 00:07:10.816
the binding energy gets more
positive meaning the electrons

00:07:10.816 --> 00:07:15.061
are less strongly bound.
Or, another way to put it,

00:07:15.061 --> 00:07:20.323
as this kinetic energy goes up
this way the binding energy gets

00:07:20.323 --> 00:07:24.907
more negative this way.
The electrons are more strongly

00:07:24.907 --> 00:07:30.000
bound as that binding energy
gets more negative.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.085
But from this kind of
experiment here we can extract

00:07:34.085 --> 00:07:39.052
what these ionization energies
are and we can extract then what

00:07:39.052 --> 00:07:43.138
the binding energies are.
Because of conservation of

00:07:43.138 --> 00:07:47.784
energy, incident energy of the
photon equals the ionization

00:07:47.784 --> 00:07:52.110
energy plus the kinetic energy.
I can rearrange this to

00:07:52.110 --> 00:07:56.837
calculate the ionization energy.
I did that for all of these

00:07:56.837 --> 00:08:01.769
three features.
Here is the incident energy of

00:08:01.769 --> 00:08:06.015
that X-ray photon.
Here is the measured kinetic

00:08:06.015 --> 00:08:09.430
energy.
The difference between the two

00:08:09.430 --> 00:08:13.861
is the ionization energy.
I solve for that there.

00:08:13.861 --> 00:08:19.307
And then that ionization energy
we know is minus the binding

00:08:19.307 --> 00:08:22.723
energy.
So if the ionization energy is

00:08:22.723 --> 00:08:28.353
21.6 eV, the binding energy here
for that 2p electron is minus

00:08:28.353 --> 00:08:31.492
21.6 eV, and for 2s,
minus 48.4 eV,

00:08:31.492 --> 00:08:37.767
and 1s, minus 870.2 eV.
I want you to notice how much

00:08:37.767 --> 00:08:43.206
more strongly bound that 1s
electron is than the electrons

00:08:43.206 --> 00:08:46.736
in the n equals 2 shell,
look at that.

00:08:46.736 --> 00:08:51.698
That 1s electron is bound by
870 eV binding energies,

00:08:51.698 --> 00:08:55.610
minus 870.
Binding energy for the n equals

00:08:55.610 --> 00:09:00.000
2 electrons is minus 48 and
minus 21.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.609
Why is that more strongly
bound?

00:09:02.609 --> 00:09:06.482
Well, that electron is in the n
equals 1 shell,

00:09:06.482 --> 00:09:11.112
which is much closer to the
nucleus where the attractive

00:09:11.112 --> 00:09:15.658
interaction between that
positive charge on the nucleus

00:09:15.658 --> 00:09:18.352
and the electron is much
greater.

00:09:18.352 --> 00:09:21.214
So this is basically the
technique.

00:09:21.214 --> 00:09:25.170
This is how we calculate those
binding energies,

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:29.632
or observe those binding
energies for the electrons in

00:09:29.632 --> 00:09:35.818
the multi-electron atom.
What I want to do now is I want

00:09:35.818 --> 00:09:41.090
to start on today's lecture.
And you don't have the lecture

