00:11:55.063 --> 00:12:00.255
We're going to talk about the
Periodic Table and the trends in

00:12:00.255 --> 00:12:04.000
the properties along the
Periodic Table.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.352
And, of course,
it's the electron

00:12:12.352 --> 00:12:16.911
configurations that allow us to
understand the structure of the

00:12:16.911 --> 00:12:20.220
Periodic Table.
But it is important to realize

00:12:20.220 --> 00:12:24.558
that the Periodic Table was
first assembled by Mendeleev and

00:12:24.558 --> 00:12:27.647
other people,
not on the basis of knowledge

00:12:27.647 --> 00:12:32.058
of the electron configurations,
but on the basis of knowledge

00:12:32.058 --> 00:12:37.521
of the similar properties --
Similar chemical and physical

00:12:37.521 --> 00:12:41.260
properties of the elements.
So, for example,

00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:43.956
lithium, sodium,
potassium here,

00:12:43.956 --> 00:12:48.826
they were all grouped in one
column because they were all

00:12:48.826 --> 00:12:54.217
found to be very soft malleable
metals that were very reactive.

00:12:54.217 --> 00:12:58.043
Helium, neon,
argon, they were all grouped in

00:12:58.043 --> 00:13:02.478
one column because they were
found to be very inert,

00:13:02.478 --> 00:13:06.190
very unreactive.
And, of course,

00:13:06.190 --> 00:13:09.761
now we understand the electron
configurations,

00:13:09.761 --> 00:13:13.412
why these elements have the
similar properties.

00:13:13.412 --> 00:13:16.666
In the case of the alkali
metals, lithium,

00:13:16.666 --> 00:13:19.841
sodium, potassium,
we've got that extra s

00:13:19.841 --> 00:13:24.603
electron, that unpaired electron
that makes those metals very

00:13:24.603 --> 00:13:26.666
reactive.
And helium, neon,

00:13:26.666 --> 00:13:31.349
argon, we've got an inner gas
shell configuration that makes

00:13:31.349 --> 00:13:38.070
those elements very unreactive.
But by the late 1800s and the

00:13:38.070 --> 00:13:43.894
early 1900s, the similar
chemical properties of atoms in

00:13:43.894 --> 00:13:49.505
a column of a Periodic Table,
that really was strongly

00:13:49.505 --> 00:13:53.847
believed, strongly believed to
an extreme.

00:13:53.847 --> 00:13:58.717
So, for example,
it was known that human beings

00:13:58.717 --> 00:14:02.000
consumed sodium,
salt.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:08.174
It was known that human beings,
our bodies contained sodium

00:14:08.174 --> 00:14:14.030
ions and potassium ions.
Well, if our body has sodium in

00:14:14.030 --> 00:14:19.992
it and potassium in it and we
consume those two elements,

00:14:19.992 --> 00:14:23.292
why not a little bit of
lithium?

00:14:23.292 --> 00:14:26.912
Okay.
About 1925 or so a soft drink

00:14:26.912 --> 00:14:32.054
came on the market.
And that soft drink,

00:14:32.054 --> 00:14:37.602
they wanted to have a lemony
flavor to that soft drink.

00:14:37.602 --> 00:14:41.506
And so, how do you get a lemony
flavor?

00:14:41.506 --> 00:14:47.054
Well, you use citric acid.
But citric acid isn't really

00:14:47.054 --> 00:14:52.089
soluble in water so,
hey, we've got to make a salt

00:14:52.089 --> 00:14:56.095
of the citric acid.
For whatever reason,

00:14:56.095 --> 00:15:03.190
a lithium citrate was made.
A lithium salt of citric acid

00:15:03.190 --> 00:15:07.259
was made.
And that soft drink was none

00:15:07.259 --> 00:15:10.340
other than 7UP.
And, in fact,

00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:16.830
if you look here it tells you
that the lithium was touted to

00:15:16.830 --> 00:15:22.220
give healthful benefits,
including an abundance of

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:26.399
energy, enthusiasm,
a clear complexion,

00:15:26.399 --> 00:15:33.000
lustrous eyes or lustrous hair
and lustrous eyes.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.594
Shinning eyes.
[LAUGHTER] And so this was on

00:15:36.594 --> 00:15:41.860
the market until the early 1950s
when finally the anti-psychotic

00:15:41.860 --> 00:15:47.126
properties of lithium were being
discovered and the side effects

00:15:47.126 --> 00:15:49.801
of lithium were being
discovered.

00:15:49.801 --> 00:15:54.566
And the 7UP was then taken off
the market, or at least the

00:15:54.566 --> 00:16:00.000
lithium citrate in the 7UP was
removed from the market.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:04.530
And, of course,
it wasn't until the early 1970s

00:16:04.530 --> 00:16:09.553
that lithium was approved as an
anti-psychotic drug,

00:16:09.553 --> 00:16:15.068
because it really is poisonous
to the human body in large

00:16:15.068 --> 00:16:18.810
amounts.
And so I really don't know how

00:16:18.810 --> 00:16:24.030
many individuals had side
effects from drinking 7UP at

00:16:24.030 --> 00:16:28.230
that time.
But the moral of the story is

00:16:28.230 --> 00:16:32.923
that even though we're about to
talk about some of the general

00:16:32.923 --> 00:16:37.384
trends in the Periodic Table,
don't put any element in your

00:16:37.384 --> 00:16:42.153
mouth just because it's in the
same column as some element that

00:16:42.153 --> 00:16:45.769
you do put in your mouth.
[LAUGHTER] True story.

00:16:45.769 --> 00:16:48.615
All right.
One of the properties we're

00:16:48.615 --> 00:16:52.000
going to talk about is the
ionization energy.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.384
And we've talked about it
already, but we haven't formally

00:16:56.384 --> 00:17:00.000
defined it.
Let me do that here.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:04.571
Here you see boron with its
electronic structure,

00:17:04.571 --> 00:17:09.714
going to boron plus.
The energy change for this

00:17:09.714 --> 00:17:14.095
reaction is what we call the
ionization energy.

00:17:14.095 --> 00:17:17.523
It's the product minus the
reactants.

00:17:17.523 --> 00:17:21.523
That's the ionization energy.
Equivalently,

00:17:21.523 --> 00:17:27.142
that ionization energy is minus
the binding energy of the 2p

00:17:27.142 --> 00:17:32.238
electron in boron.
This is a process that is

00:17:32.238 --> 00:17:36.000
removing the least strongly
bound electron.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:40.298
When we remove the least
strongly bound electron,

00:17:40.298 --> 00:17:45.850
the energy that is required to
do that is called the ionization

00:17:45.850 --> 00:17:47.910
energy.
And, more fully,

00:17:47.910 --> 00:17:50.776
it's the first ionization
energy.

00:17:50.776 --> 00:17:55.611
It is the energy to remove the
electron from this HOAO,

00:17:55.611 --> 00:18:00.000
the highest occupied atomic
orbital.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.573
Or, the least strongly bound
electron.

00:18:03.573 --> 00:18:07.242
Same idea.
This is the highest occupied

00:18:07.242 --> 00:18:10.140
atomic orbital.
Now, generally,

00:18:10.140 --> 00:18:15.644
when we say ionization energy
we mean the first ionization

00:18:15.644 --> 00:18:18.928
energy.
We often leave out the word

00:18:18.928 --> 00:18:22.211
"first".
So whenever you look up an

00:18:22.211 --> 00:18:26.750
ionization energy,
implied in that is that it is

00:18:26.750 --> 00:18:33.469
the first ionization energy --
The energy to remove the least

00:18:33.469 --> 00:18:37.832
strongly bound electron.
The second ionization energy,

00:18:37.832 --> 00:18:41.949
well, that is the energy
required to remove another

00:18:41.949 --> 00:18:45.159
electron.
